review.reviewBody:
Love the shoe’s look and performance so far. But, I had to put an extra cushion in. The footbed it came with is plenty comfortable but without the extra height the sides of the shoes rubbed very uncomfortably on the bottoms of my ankles. After wearing them the sides seem to have softened some but in my perfect world they would have been made a tad lower. Nonetheless with the small amount of lift the cushion provides along with the apparent softening of the sides I’m very happy with the look and performance of the shoes.

I think the shoes run a little large based on shoes I normally wear - but following thee Keen size guide I ordered what I thought would be too small but turned out correct.
review.name: Very Pleased, but. . .

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] The true renaissance show. From work to gardening to hiking to night on the town. Does it all great.

review.reviewBody: I’m very happy with my new Keen boots. They’re ideal for a winter day when it’s cold but there isn’t a lot of fresh snow.

review.reviewBody: It is a well built shoe but that is all. I returned my pair after I wore them for two days since the boot of the shoe is too tall and rubbed under my ankle. The fit is not true at all also. I usually wear a 13 and according to Keen's size calculator, I should need a 13. Nope! they are at least a full size oversized. The sole is supposed to have extra insulation to avoid the cold coming from the surface and that actually makes the shoe colder. I don't like to give negative reviews but this shoe is not what it is described.
review.name: Not happy with several things about this shoe

review.reviewBody: As usual on Keen shoes, the soles are great but the uppers just don’t work for me. Have wide feet and Keen sizes are inconsistent so ordered sizes 12 and 13. 13 was too big and the 12 too tight around top. The tops rub across the ankle on both. So returned them.
review.name: Nice but not for me

review.itemreviewed: Field Boot Mid WP Lace Up Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody: I've been buying and wearing Timbs for over 30 years, but after this experience with the Field Boot, I'm not sure I'll ever purchase Timbs ever again. The second time I wore these boots, the sole completely disintegrated while I was out. Pieces of the sole started breaking apart as I stepped out of my car, leaving me embarrassed - to add, I was an hour away from home and I had to find a department store just to buy another pair of shoes because the boots were unusable. By the time I walked into a store to buy replacement shoes I had no outsoles left - it looked like I was wearing wrestling shoes. Literally ruined my lunch date. This is not the quality I've come to expect from Timberland. I've always trusted this brand for its durability, but this experience has completely shattered my confidence in their products. Save your money and avoid this boot at all costs. If this is what Timberland calls "quality" now, they've lost a lifelong customer.
review.name: Extremely Disappointed - Sole Completely Disintegrated

review.reviewBody: Roomy, so one can wear a sweater underneath. Very lightweight in feel but keeps me warm. Didn't make any annoying noise when I walk.  Glad I purchased it.
review.name: Great jacket

review.reviewBody: I love this puffy, it's a great light weight shoulder season coat. It's light and thin enough to layer under a shell for cold days too. And I get tons of compliments on the color. The only reason I didn't give 5 stars is the plastic zipper isn't that great.
review.name: Great lightweight puffy

review.reviewBody: This a nice warm jacket that is really quite thin, however it keeps you nicely insulated against the cold. It packs into one of the pockets and seems to be wearing well. My only complaint is a general one - I wish I could get a size smaller but my hips are too big for that.
review.name: Lightweight and warm

review.reviewBody: Comfy and warm. Wanted something synthetic because I live in SE AK where it rains all the time

Best jacket ever!!!  This is my go to for everyday life, backpacking, day hiking and worn under my ski jacket for extra warmth.  I love this jacket.  It’s lightweight, packs down small but it’s so warm.  It’s made with quality products and holds up to most activities.  It does shed some of material from inside like a down jacket but that’s not a big deal for me.  The price is right especially if you’re on a budget.  Great job OR, I own two and planning on another.
review.name: I Own Two!!!  Soon To Be Three!!!

review.reviewBody: This jacket is super light and easy to pack and carry.  I ordered the white one and the only con I would mention is that you can see the stuffing in the coat when you hold it up to the light.  The white material looks a little see through in certain lighting.  Would highly recommend other than that.

I bought this jacket for its features and color. When it arrived the jacket looked patchy or stained, almost. Looking closer, I saw the material was so thin I could see the gaps in the filling of the jackets. It might have been less noticeable with other color options, but the poor quality of fill  made me question the jacket in general. I have other OR products that I love, and have bought from Backcountry before. I returned this jacket for a refund, which was a pretty easy process. This could have been a one-off experience for me, but it was a little disappointing coming from some brands I really support.
review.name: Avoid the yellow color

review.reviewBody:
I bought this coat for a trip to Iceland and the Faroe Islands (currently 9 days into a 3 week trip).  On the 4th day of wearing this coat, generally covered with a rain jacket, I noticed a tear on the right elbow.  So, I have to agree with another reviewer that the fabric is not durable.  The hole is covered with duct tape and I will contact Backcountry on my return home in 2 weeks.

On the plus side, the coat is much warmer and wind resistant than expected.  Also, it's very light weight and compressed into a relatively small package.  I'm just really sorry that it ripped on the 4th day I wore it.  I would not purchase this jacket again as a result.
review.name: Overall nice, but fragile fabric

review.reviewBody: Love this jacket. Its warm with no bulk. Its so lightweight I forget I'm wearing it. It breathes great on hikes and packs down small when the sun comes out. I ordered the Naval blue and the color is beautiful, not as boring as black but still neutral enough to match any outfit. The fit is very flattering. I have long arms and most sleeves are too short but this jacket is perfect!
review.name: A great jacket for transition seasons

review.reviewBody: Love this jacket. It's warm, while being lightweight. Especially love the color I purchased! I also purchased same jacket in Men's....for my husband. He doesn't get it until his birthday...but I know he will love it.
review.name: New to Outdoor Research

review.reviewBody: Won this bag now its the main bag I use, meant to be a winter bag but I've used it for backpacking in chiacgo basin and worked great with the full weight of my gear then straps and modulations of it made it a great day bag to get the 4, 14ers around the area. Hunter orange for saftey!

review.reviewBody:
Actually pretty swell! carries well, loads of space but also able to be slim, interesting material,

Starting at the material. It is super tough and water wouldn’t dream of going through it. That being said it will hold water.

For the lid design, as said in another review if the bag isn’t moderately full there is a gap between the lid and bag that just begs for water to jump into. When water gets in it then sits. Thus the reason for my 3 stars. Thankfully, in this case, Fjallraven doesn’t tape the seams.
The lid style used on the ulvo roll top would be perfect! You would then be able to ditch the lid and still have a nicely sealed pack. Just saying I’d pay top dollar for that.


The straps and hip belt are definitely for winter as you will sweat in the summer. Perhaps a summer version or pads sold extra to add a mesh would be cool. 

Other than that the bag rocks. A kind a super durable sack that is comfortable with heavy loads and get loads of compliments. Seems like it is so tough it might speak at my funeral.
review.name: Actually Almost Perfect

review.reviewBody:
I've had the backpack for over a year now and I'm more then happy with.

The only complained is the same as Sam W., no hole for a camel-bag "straw".
This came as a missive surprise to me while packing for a 2 week hike. The sleeve for the camel-bag is designed so well, with extra hoops to keep it well in place, that I was convinced for a minute that must have missed the hole or that I was to stupid to find it.

Would still rate it 10/10 since it can go trough the main opening but still there should be a dictated space for it.
review.name: close to perfection

review.reviewBody: While this pack is fabulous in all seasons- i really love it for winter. great contrast with the snow = great visibility. Strap features on the outer sides allow me to strap on my skis or my snowshoes securely. Easy attachments for gear on the outside and great access on the inside. This pack was with me during a long, wet-heavy snow day and everything inside stayed dry. Plenty of room inside for my roll up sled, extra layers, and avalanche rescue gear. Plus a comfortable fit and INCREDIBLY light!!
review.name: Best Winter Pack

review.reviewBody: I submitted Mt. Kilimanjaro with this pack. It was the perfect size and shape to hike with whatever you needed rain or shine through 5 climate zones every day. I loved the simplicity and ability to carry a load of heavy gear with the removable wooden slats. The one recommendation that I can give is to make it more hydration pack friendly. There is an excellent sleeve for the hydration pack on the inside, but there should be holes for the hydration pack hoses. Without strategic holes, the hoses have to drop in through the top draw-string area, and in doing so, it creates an opening between the top section and the main backpack where water can get right through if it rains. Strategically placed hose holes (one on both sides) would make this pack perfect.

I picked this pack up specifically for winter backcountry travel for the flexibility of being able to swap between snowshoes and skis with great strap options on the outside for skis and snowshoes and waterproof gear storage on the inside. The unexpected bonus is how incredibly durable and lightweight this pack is, not to mention high visibility from afar. I put this pack to the test on Day 1 of Avalanche School when we found ourselves standing in rain and wind for five hours, packs setting in snow (even buried a few times). Getting in and out of the main compartment quickly for rescue gear was essential, as was ensuring I could get it quickly battened up tight again to keep weather out. Pack performed flawlessly- keeping everything dry and accessible. I’ll be adding a coat of repellent spray just for good measure- but this is the perfect pack.
review.name: Epic waterproof put to the test

review.reviewBody: I picked up the Bergtagen 38 last summer and it has quickly become my pack of choice for adventures that take me into the mountains.  Whether afternoon trips with a mile or two approach to a local crag, or longer missions to bag a peak it has become the bag I reach for.  It distributes weight really nicely,  and is spacious enough to fit all of your gear. The gear pocket's inside plus the top pocket make keeping your small items organized easy.  When you want it to be a little lighter, stripping it of it's stays, hip belt, and lid is quick and easy, and putting it back together afterwards is just as quick.  The waterproof Bergshell material means not having to think about a rain cover and whether your stuff will be soaked on those mountain days when the weather is changing every 30 minutes.  The rope strap on top, the storage loops for ice axes/poles, and the hydration system compatibility are features that you won't want to be without after using the Bergtagen 38 a few times.  I highly recommend this pack to anyone who likes to get out for adventures in the mountains that require more gear than just the bare essentials.
review.name: Go to Pack for  Mountain Adventures

review.reviewBody: These climb a lot better than my TC Pros, albeit, more fitted.
review.name: top notch

review.reviewBody: Was on the fence about these shoes… absolute beaut of a purchase! Would 10/10 recommend to a friend. Super grippy, comfortable and feel quality! I ordered .5 up in size and was a perfect fit for me!
review.name: Way better than expected!

review.reviewBody: Have had these shoes over a year now and wanted to submit a review. The rubber is confident, the fit is comfortable, and the break in period wasn't too bad depending on how often you climb. Have gone through the range of single pitch routes, multi pitch routes, and a few alpine climbs and have really enjoyed the performance and feel especially on the longer days. This was my first BD shoe and I will certainly buy these again when current pair is retired. I would recommend trying them on as they were not my typical sizing from other brands.
review.name: Great fit and performance

review.reviewBody:
I’ve been putting them through the wringer, through multi-hour climb sessions and I’m the only person who doesn’t have to take their shoes off. While there’s still an occasional shoe fart, they perform great, doing well with slab smearing and edging on every hold I’ve put them on. Can’t recommend enough!
I do normally wear a 13-14 and went for a 13 in this which fit great!
review.name: Super Comfortable

review.reviewBody: I had to return and order a full size up. Actual size was close but far more scrunched in the toes than other brands. Sized up and feels perfect. Amazing grip
review.name: Excellent

review.reviewBody:
So far they’ve been great! Normally wear a 13.5-14 street shoe, depending on the brand, decided to risk it for the biscuit and order a 13 in spite of everyone saying to go up. They ended up fitting perfectly to be comfortable for a long day at the crag but still edge great on small holds due to the slight camber. The laces are a great addition and for someone with a, typically, low volume heel, these are perhaps the first to fit perfectly. Excited to defy gravity more in these!

*There was a bit of the shoe farting but that’s all but disappeared after a few climbs. If I hear it walking around, I just treat it as a reminder to re-tie my laces.
review.name: Risk it for the biscuit

review.reviewBody: Can't remember if I've reviewed this already, but I can say again, BD knocked it out of the park with the aspect pro. Is it really better than the TC Pro? Comfort for all-day - YES. Stuffing the shoe into a crack - YES. Technical performance - Similar. But BEWARE - the sizing on BD shoes is OFF...I have to size UP a full size, maybe even a size and a half.
review.name: Better than TC Pro?

review.reviewBody:
I got this pair about 2-3 weeks ago, climbed 8-10 days with them, and loved the fit and the grip, despite the foot farts. Anyways, the Glue started to detach at certain spots (near the small toe on both feet and on the inner sides. I don't think it is normal for such a nice and performing shoe. 

Still love these shoes, but I remain a little dissapointed.
review.name: Good shoes, but the glue is kind of bad.

review.reviewBody:
I had to put some miles on these shoes before writing a review. So i sought out to climb a wide range of styles before authoring an opinion. 
At first receiving these shoes, I was impress d with the build quality and amount of padding on them. They looked well put together and were quite cushiony in all the right spots. 
Fit; On first try, the fit seemed tight. I got them 1/2 size bigger than my street shoe. Everything I read said to go 1 size bigger, but I took a chance and split the difference. They felt tight and I almost sent them back. I decided to take them out anyway and after wearing them for a few minutes, the padding started to mold to my feet and the tightness started to go away. After a few routes, they fit like a glove. I wouldn’t want them any bigger for techy climbing. I was able to throw down a few .13’s and several .12’s on the first day of wearing them. Very impressive! 
Performance; The rubber was good. No complaints there. The weather was in the mid 70’s most of the time so not sure about how it preforms in really hot or cold conditions. The edging ability was good. They fit into thin cracks and were comfortable in wider cracks, awkward widths and offwidths. No gobies on the ankles. 
The shoes seem to fit a bit wider toebox which is good for older feet with issues like bunions. The last was flat and stuff which helped my arthritic toes as well. 

Overall I’m impressed. I’ve been longtime user of the TCPros, but since they changed the design, I haven’t been that happy with them. These are an improvement on the old TCPros and way better than the newer designed ones. 
Durability; so far they have no issues , but I’ve only climbed around 50 routes in about 4 days out so we’ll see. BD is newer on the shoe market so I had some skepticism when these came out. Well, they came onto the market swinging and delivered a knockout blow in the all day trad shoe market. These will be my new go to’s for sure.
review.name: New go to!

review.reviewBody:
Overall: I think these are the most comfortable crack climbing shoe I have ever worn. However, it is one of the worst fitting shoes despite a well fitting shoe.

The poor fit leads to a subpar performance while edging or smearing. The shoe tends to bunch and crease when bent at the toes in all the wrong places which leaves you feeling as if the shoe is too big or roomy in the toe box. This was most noticed when face climbing but did not really affect the jamming performance.

Everyone's foot is different but best to try these on in person before ordering as these were sized up 1 full size from my typical climbing shoe size.
review.name: Superb Comfort - Sub Par Fit

name: Aspect Pro Climbing Shoes

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I loved these boots, lightweight and very comfortable. The top lace hook would sometimes catch on the lace from the other boot but I fixed that by got double lacing through the lace hooks. The problem arose when the place my foot bends on the tow box wore a hole and now they are not longer water proof. I’m bummed.
review.name: Loved them, until I didn’t
comment: Thank you for your feedback on the X ULTRA 360 MID CLIMASALOMON WATERPROOF. We're glad to hear you loved their lightweight and comfortable design. We're sorry to learn about the issue with the toe box wearing out and losing waterproofing. Your experience is important to us, and we will use your feedback to improve our products.

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: This boot provides great support and foot protection for hiking on rocky trails.  Love them and thinking about buying the low rise hiking shoes
review.name: Great support and lightweight

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: bought these boots a month ago.  they are great at stabilizing feet and therefore knees.  generous toe box is a relief.  nicely done.
review.name: super great boots

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought two pairs of these for a hiking retreat, which was a risky choice. Nonetheless, these boots were comfortable from the start. Interchanging both pairs every other day helped to eliminate blisters. I only left my trip with one painless blister on the heel. I am a 7.5 and these were true to size.
review.name: Comfortable from the start

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I kicked one of the upper lace hooks while hiking in the boots and it popped off.  These should be riveted into the boot.  But instead they are pushed into some sort of reviving plate and maybe glued there? Very poor design for serous hikers who may be miles into the backcountry and have these boots break.
review.name: Problem with lace hooks
comment: Hi. We’re sorry for any inconvenience. We’re glad to confirm to you that a case has been opened to address your concerns, and we’re waiting for your answer. Please check your inbox!

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought them a month ago. They're extremely light, very comfortable, provide so much support. I just can't get enough of them! My new favorite hiking boots
review.name: Amazing hiking shoes

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
This boot is amazing!  My second pair, comfortable from the moment you put it on.  Fit, function and durable. I wear these nearly every day.  They are the most practical and functional boots I have ever owned.  I will keep using them.  Love the Salomon products!
Thank you for making great footwear.
review.name: Great Boot!

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I bought these shoes about a month ago and love how they fit and that they’re waterproof!
review.name: Super comfy fit!

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I purchased these boots a couple of months ago to replace a pair I purchased that were advertised as waterproof, but were not. I had the opportunity to hike and walk in both dry and wet conditions. First, I would say that these boots are very comfortable from the first day. There was no breaking in period. Second, I wore the boots on daily walks in wet grass and in over-the-toe puddles, and they kept my feet completely dry. I am pleased to date. My hope is they will stay waterproof for as long as the sole lasts. That is how long my last 2 pair of Salomon hiking boots did which was for over 10 years each..
review.name: So far so good.

review.itemreviewed: X Ultra 360 Mid CSWP Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
So glad I got these boots. I was looking for a hiking boot with ankle stability but light and waterproof. I walk my dogs in rough footing woods and fields every day and am nearing 70.
Important to have dependable footwear. I feel they are perfect for every season except summer, when they may be a little more boot than needed. Overall very good choice
review.name: Light waterproof comfy

I was apprehensive at first as I was getting some rubbing on my wee toe at a seam, but stuck with them for a few days and as they have softened up, they have become nice and comfy. Very happy with them, Ive dropped it a star (would have been half a star but it wont let me) as id say they aren't as airy as i was hoping but still a lot more so than a normal trainer. Im usually a size 9.5 but went with a UK 10, as from experience of another pair of shoes find a half size up is better and feel the same with these..

review.reviewBody:
I picked up a pair of "water shoes" this summer that I hesitated to purchase in its previous  handful of versions. I bought the Saloman Tech Amphibian 5 in a men's 11.5, a half size smaller than my normal size, based on the sizing details and exchanged them for an even smaller 11 after trying them on, with and without socks. They exceeded my expectations in the areas of water entry/exit, foot protection and surface grip. 

My reason for acquiring them was to use them for crossing streams in the backcountry, but this summer I have found them to be so utilitarian during camping, hiking and everyday life. They are so lightweight and quick to slip on/off that they stayed just outside of the tent within an arm's reach. I recently wore them on a warm, afternoon hike on a local trail known for being rocky and slippery. I loved feeling the breeze flow through the mesh during the hottest section of woods. I was shocked at how stable they felt under foot and I was able to step confidently in otherwise treacherous conditions. I want to remind the readers that they are mesh, water shoes and of course their stability shouldn't be compared to hiking boots or technical, trail running gear. 

In general, if you're looking for an adventurous shoe that can be useful for a wide range of wet and dry activities, I'd highly recommend that you purchase them and I suggest that you get a full size smaller than the norm, since they are easily loosened at the heel.
review.name: Excellent Summer Shoes!

review.reviewBody:
I have wide feet, so in length I should be around a 10, but I always need a 10.5 (45 EU) - read some reviews saying these were a bit too snug, but I chanced my arm and couldn't be happier with the fit.
They're a light but solid build that I often wear in the slipper style, with the back tucked down under my heel - this is an excellent design feature for recovery/relax after walking - with the benefit of being able to pull the back up to keep the shoe on in case you need to go some distance.
One slight downside is I occasionally get the left cord adjustment finding it's way into the shoe and putting pressure on foot, but I found a way to tuck it in tight to it's buckle and haven't had the problem happen since.
The only other caveat would be that these are a much brighter Orange than the photos or the description of "Spice Route/Burnt Henna..." might lead you to believe, but if you're comfortable rocking dayglo orange, you'll be fine. 
Oh, I also read some saying they found them slippy in wet conditions, but that's not my experience and have always found the soles grippy and solid under foot, though I can imagine if you were bouldering over some slimy rocks, you might want to place your feet more carefully.
review.name: Yeah, I love these.

I climb Camelback Mountain in Phoenix, Arizona every day. It's 5-miles, 2,400' of granite boulders with no soft places, no dirt, only sharp-edged rocks to tear up your boots. The mountain has torn up many lesser shoes and shredded all competitors. I've hiked with XA Pro 3D for ten years and recently switched to the Ultra 360 (same shoe, better padding). Everyone I've recommended them to has stuck with them. 

Nothing comes close! I highly recommend these for tough terrain. (They'll probably do great at easy terrain too, but I don't go there.)

review.reviewBody:
Was looking for a high-visibility running jacket similar to the Patagonia Houdini Air (wind resistance + breathability).  I have both the regular Houdini  (size L) and Houdini Air (M). Keeping this in M.

FIT:  I'm 5'1, 150 lbs, 34DD, round belly. With a Smartwool 250 baselayer or a thin long-sleeved cotton t, fit is close to the body, but not tight (Corresponding Houdini sizes run much slimmer); pretty forgiving of my belly :) Perfect length for me, falling around mid-hip; Houdinis are longer, falling below my butt.  

FEEL/FUNCTION:  I've worn this for multiple runs (incl. light rain, strong wind).  This feels somewhere in-between the Houdinis in terms of wind-blocking and breathability.  V. light rain beaded on the surface of the jacket, but left a mark when smushed into the fabric.  Material is a matte, slightly stretchy, more fabric-y (vs. plastic-y) material - like a slightly thicker/heavier Air.  Hood fits over thick pony-tail securely when fully zipped, and stays in strong wind.  Doubles as a running and casual jacket better than the Houdinis due to a more forgiving fit  around the mid-section (for looser-fitting street clothes), shorter length (more flattering for my short stature), and zippered side pockets.  Packs down small enough for an upcoming 2.5 week trip to Europe (24L bag).  

COLOR:  Azalea appears neon coral in the pictures, which is what originally attracted me. Unfortunately, it actually is not neon at all, and is more like a salmon pink that leans more pink than orange. So disappointing. It is slightly see-through.  LOVE the green (Grove) colorway - something about the color + matte fabric texture + matching zippers makes it look SO smooth and rich and clean.  Did not intend to get this color, but decided to try (and keep!) it based on the (accurate) pictures.
review.name: flattering fit

review.reviewBody: These things are super light, feel nice in the hand, and have a decent gate action. That said, I’ve found that the screw likes to lock closed after being loaded, even after something static like anchoring. I would unload it, then have to use two hands to break the screw loose to unlock it. Not ideal when trying to release from an anchor to rappel. I own like 5 of these, and experienced this on multiple of them, so not isolated to a possibly defective single carabiner. They still do their job and are light, so I’ll keep using them for the time being. I just won’t rely on them for situations where one-handed operation is required. Black Diamond and others should also be aware.

review.reviewBody: Mounted traditional on a new pair of Volkl Mantra M5 in 178cm for me.  I'm certainly comfortable skiing anything in the resort, I call myself lower advanced as I have friends whom shoot commercials, competed in olympics, etc.. They are advanced.  These bindings are nice.  I had Marker Griffon before.  I notice with the low "toe" it take a little more to get the fat ski on edge, but super solid feel.  The clicking in is easier and as a result of taking less energy, you also don't get the massive "thud" of the marker.  Having said that, I only run DIN at 7 and ski pretty steep terrain in full bumps and I've had ZERO issue with releasing.  To date I haven't crashed so I can't speak to release during crash, but skiing advanced terrain they hold well at lower DINs.  If I had any complaint, you need to have the heal go straight down into the rear to get the solid snap.  if your a bit sideways or lazy it'll "latch" but won't snap and then you realize it's not quite right.  So in the morning, I snap in "proper" and look to verify and it's never an issue.   I would recommend for new sticks if you like Tyrolia.  To me, Griffon/attack/other.  It's just a good binding and it does the job.  The red looks nice with the red accent ski's.  By the way more easy to unlock than Griffon at the end of the day, but who cares about that, your going for a beer at the bottom. Duuh
review.name: Tyrolia Attack13 binding in red

I bought a pair of solid leather TEVA hiking boots many years ago when I lived in Ohio, and they fit my feet like a second skin. review.reviewBody: This shoe is unreal for indoor climbing or soft sandstone type rock.  The RS rubber should legitimately be banned from competition.  It's like super gluing your foot to volumes.  Not a beginner shoe, very aggressive sizing, I went half size down and my toes go numb after a few minutes but the rubber is soft and I expect it to mold to my foot in another session or two.  It's already more comfortable than when I got it.  If you have downsized other shoes by multiple sizes like LaSpo, this is not the shoe to go 3 sizes down on.  My TN Pro from Unparallel is street size and fits almost perfectly but a little more comfortable, half size down on Flagship feels just right for aggressive fit.
review.name: Literally cheating, Aid Shoe

review.reviewBody: I got curious about these shoes after seeing more and more people Bouldering in them at my local gym; and hearing the Staff there rave about them.  Be forewarned:  The entrance to these shoes is SMALL, and could trick you into thinking you need to size up.  Better to force your way in and then decide if you have on the correct size.  I think you will notice 3 separate features of these shows:  First, the forefoot offers nice concavity, sending force over to your big toe.  And the forefoot is pretty rigid, offering you better edging than you might have expected.  Kind of like the Skwama; but the Flagship seems a bit more rigid up front, IMO.  Second, the midfoot is pretty flexible = a surprise behind such a stable forefoot.  Some people might not like how flexible this shoe is in the middle; other people might find this feature especially attractive.  Your option!  And finally, the heel is quite robust.  I do not have these super-tight, so the heel slid a micro-cm, then LOCKED onto my heel.  If you get them in a "performance" fit, you need not worry about your heel hooks.    My other shoes are all super stiff, so these a a departure for me.  But I have to tell you, they are a delight to climb and Boulder in, and perform above what I/you might expect before actually slipping into them.  With other shoes now North of $200, the price point of these is also a pleasant respite.
review.name: Interesting Combination Of Features

review.reviewBody: Has a good ring to it, looks good, and doesn't take up too much room
review.name: Dope Bell

review.reviewBody: Great little bell with a classic sound and tasteful aesthetic. Not the loudest but that's likely a product of the shape and smaller surface area that can vibrate, which is a trade-off I will take. It's slim profile doesn't clutter up my handlebars which is especially nice on my sleek road bike aero-bars and also my already tech-heavy mountain bike handlebars.
review.name: On 5 of my bikes now

review.reviewBody:
I love the form factor.  SO small on the bar, barely visible.  I got plenty of compliments at the trailhead "wait...is that a bell?"  it snaps onto the bar positively and is easy to install.  The piece of leather keeps the bar from being scratched which is a nice touch.  I've crashed several times with the bell on the bar and it hasn't been ripped off or scratched even, so the form factor clearly has a function.

The downsides are a bit more glaring though.  First is the volume.  Its just not loud enough.  No matter how hard you pull back the striker the sound stays the same.  I have made sure the bell isnt contacting the grip or shifter or anything else that would mute its sound.  The second thing is the spring on the striker lever wears out, so now its just loose and when I go downhill it rattles and rings constantly.  Yes I know I said I crashed a bunch above, but I made sure the lever wasn't damaged.  Its just worn out.  If I wanted that, I would have bought a timber bell.
review.name: Good, but has a couple flaws

review.reviewBody: This has worked for me while riding on dirt trails. So far the people have been able to hear it. Nice sleek design.

I usually wear Scarpa Vapor V size EU36,5. I ordered the Sensors EU 36 knowing these are softer than the Vapors and thought they would be great after a bit of wear.
Once I received them I realized they are way smaller than I expected. I'm going to order a new pair in EU37,5.

review.reviewBody: Shoes came out of the box very flexible, required little time to break in. Rubber is sticky and soft, great edging ability. Heels needs some work as it tends to slip when doing heel hook.
review.name: Great Rubber, heels needs improvement

review.reviewBody: Still trying to break these in. I ordered .5 size down (based off all the review recommendations). You should order true size or size up. These are aggressive and make smearing easy. I can feel all the small holds! Great buy, especially when on sale
review.name: Great aggressive shoe

review.reviewBody: I asked some experts what size to get with these shoes and was told a 9. For reference I'm normally a 10. I ended up returning these and got La Sportiva Kubo in a 9 which fit way better than these. Not sure why brands are so off when it comes to shoes but oh well.
review.name: too small

review.reviewBody: I picked up a pair of these on sale, figuring I would try them out and see if Red Chilis can keep up with the big names in climbing shoes. So far they have been great for gym bouldering: sticky, soft but not too soft, and they fit like a glove. I wear a 13 in street shoes and bought a 12 for these and could definitely not have gone any smaller, but after a few sessions they are good to wear for a few problems at a time before my feet need a break.
review.name: Been loving these shoes for the gym!

review.reviewBody: I wear street shoes 7.5, which usually also works for climbing shoes from LaSportiva and 5.10.  So I tried 7.5 in these and boy were they extremely small.  Judging by how small they are , I'll probably have to try 9.5 or 10.  Similar thing happened to me with Evolv shoes.  I just don't get it how far off some manufacturers are with their sizing.

review.reviewBody: I'm ordering a second pair of these!  I've had the first pair for a couple of years now, and they are very durable and fit great (and still in great shape).  I've used them for Class 3 - 14ers, hiking, snowshoeing and trekking in Italy and love them!
review.name: Best Softshell Pants!

review.reviewBody:
These get 100 days of use a year in various wilderness settings. Biking, XC Skiing, bushcraft, seem to hold up season after season. These aren't carhartts... 

Not the best around fire, holes will melt with sparks as with any thin synthetic. 

Cinchable hem at ankles allowed you to pull pants up to knees easily for extra breathability. 

I had a snap on one of the cinches break. Would be nice if Mammut included an extra snap so that you can repair with like hardware. 

Great stretch and mobility. 

For some reason when paired with Murino wool boxers smell crept up. Work fine with cotton. 

Keep pockets zipped can tear if left open often.
review.name: Great simple pants. Size up.

review.reviewBody: Durable, comfortable, fitted pants. Light weight for how tough they are. So far used for hiking in Canadian Rockies where some leg contact with rock inevitable but pants stood up to the test and provided the needed protection. Pants are appropriate for many activities including hiking, scrambling, mountaineering, and rock climbing. Good protection from rock abrasion, wind, cold and some water proofness. Suitable for all levels of participant.
review.name: Well-fitted, comfortable, protective pants

review.reviewBody: I put these pants to the test by wearing them for 6 days straight while on a glacier trip... These were relatively breathable pants, although a bit thick for summer glacier days. There were times where they'd be too hot and I wish they had side vents. I did puncture a few holes in the legs with my crampons, but wouldn't expect these semi-entry level pants to prevent that. I did notice that dirt got stuck to the pants easily, so was hard to keep them clean. All considered, they were great pants that I'll continue to use for similar alpine & mountaineering objectives. I wouldn't recommend them for touring unless it's a day where your internal temperature fluctuates too much
review.name: Decent Softshell Pants- May be better options

review.reviewBody:
The whole sizing situation can be a bit perplexing, echoing what others have already pointed out with different pants. So, my usual gig is a 32 in regular pants. So, I went ahead and snagged both these Courmayeur ones and the Aenergy Light SO pants, both in a trusty 32.

Now, the Aenergy buddies fit just right, got a little breathing space which is cool because they've got those nifty tie strings to do a little cinching if needed. But now, these Courmayeur fellas, whoa, they're like snug city, bordering on that 30 or maybe even a 29 vibe. But hey, they do stretch a tad, so they manage to squeeze in there. Technically a fit, but definitely hugging tight.

I was sort of banking on the Courmayeur pair giving me some extra play, considering they seem pretty heavy-duty and I had dreams of sliding on some tights underneath for extra toasty ventures. But darn, no such luck. These pants are like, "Sorry mate, no extra room on the guest list, we're full."

In hindsight, I'd probably have gone with a 34 for the Courmayeur champs, and stuck to my guns with a 32 for the Aenergy champs. Just my two cents!
review.name: Fantastic product, confusing sizing

review.reviewBody:
I bought these on a whim, some guy on the proj said they held up to a fair amount of offwidth abuse so I figured I’d give em a shot, and man am I glad I made that call!

Sizing seems perfect for me, I bought a 30 reg and they fit like I’d expect em to. The hips have a built in tensioning system that uses Velcro, but not like cheap 90s Velcro, more like space age Swiss sexy Velcro. The ankles have nice snap clips so you can snug em up if you’re jamming your feet in cracks.

I’ve used them climbing in the PNW on chilly days and in some poor weather conditions, they’ve always kept me warm and dry. I did a few days of bolting in them and they held up very well to that abuse. I even rocked em on an ice climbing trip and they seem to perform exceptionally well in the cold and wet conditions, honestly they never soaked thru even after hours out in the elements.

These are an all around great pant and active layer for adventures in the mountains, they also make a great travel pant as they look good in the city and stay deceptively clean looking even after being abused in the backcountry.

I plan on buying a few more pairs to have color options.

Yes, you should buy them.
review.name: Fantastic climbing pants

review.reviewBody: love these pants. kept me very warm and dry quickly when they get wet. great to use in the snow or even when it's drizzling out. the fit makes them very stylish so you can go from the mountains into the city without anyone giving you a second look. I liked velcro waistband way more than I thought it would and helps get the pants as tight or loose as you'd like. the zipper also goes all the way up to the top button which, for whatever reason, makes everything feel more secure.
review.name: functional & stylish

review.reviewBody: Great fit and comfort through a full range of movements. Durable and light fabric that doesn't chafe skin under the harness. Well placed front zipper pocket that rides ideally below leg loops.  I use these cragging and on alpine walls. I may try them for a skimo/touring pant this winter. So far, I'm stoked I got these pants!
review.name: Excellent cool and cold weather climbing pants!

review.reviewBody:
I'm 6'0, 175 lbs and usually wear a 32 waist. I ordered the 48 and it is an exact fit, but not much room for tucking layers or putting over anything. Waist is adjustable thankfully, so it will work great. 
If I'm in tougher elements, I'd likely wear my Aenergy Hardshell pants over these just because I'm in the PNW and want to prevent any wetness whatsoever. On ski touring/hiking days in Utah/Montana where it is drier, this is what I'd be wearing. Very lightweight softshell, breathable, and holds up surprisingly well. 

I used these on Mt. Rainer for everything besides the final summit where I threw on hardshells over them. On the way down, I slid on my butt in summer conditions and did not get wet until the very end. They dried quickly and are a great option for something more active/light where you don't expect heavy wind or wet conditions. 

I've got an Arcteryx softshell pant that I retired for these and have no regrets.
review.name: Arcteryx level durability, great for non-wet activities

review.reviewBody: I've used these extensively on hikes and climbs in the Northeast over the past year and a half and they are durable and effective in a variety of conditions. That being said, there are two features I do not like. First, the belt system is a case of reinventing the wheel. It is similar to velcro but far less effective, and I find it coming off frequently. Moreover, there are no belt loops, so you have to use this system. Second, there are small metal hooks that attach the bottom of the pant to your shoelace. They are designed to keep your pants from riding up your legs, but I do not have this issue regardless of if they are hooked, and more often, they are rather uncomfortable, irritating the ankle. These pants perform well; however, I cannot recommend this product to others with the two flaws mentioned above.
review.name: Two Issues But Otherwise a Solid Outdoor Pant

review.itemreviewed: Speedgoat 5 GTX Spike Trail Run Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I'm so glad that I made this purchase. They are pricey but well worth it when the roads are covered with snow and/or ice. Excellent traction and waterproof (for the most part), too. The shoe fits well, and is also great for muddy, sloppy trails without snow. My only beef about the shoes would be the low heel cup; it sits lower than I am used to and that's where the mud/snow/water can seep in. Otherwise, I would highly recommend this shoe to any runner who has to navigate through snow, ice, or mud.
review.name: Hoka Speedgoat GTX Spike saves the day when it snows!

review.itemreviewed: Speedgoat 5 GTX Spike Trail Run Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: These would've been great to walk outside in the icy weather conditions. The knot on the stitching (and possibly show glue) on one side of the tongue on one of the shoes would rub on the top of my foot when I walked. I don't know if it was just this particular pair and considered exchanging for the same, but didn't want to chance it. I wish Hoka would make the comfortable padded tongues like they have on the Bondi 7 and consider placing these cleats on some of their other styles.
review.name: Has potential but had a few flaws

review.itemreviewed: Speedgoat 5 GTX Spike Trail Run Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I am so happy that HOKA has small sized shoes!!! So hard to find size 5 wide. The speed goat GTX spiked shoe however does not come in wide but...I sized up a half size to 5.5 so I can wear heavy winter sox and the shoe fits perfectly, has a good array of spikes and so far has worked well. Good thickness in the sole and insoles, my feet did not get cold in the recent steep hike I did at 18 degrees F and gripped the frozen ground well, except in glare ice where even Kahtoola's were not gripping. I am happy with this shoe
review.name: SpeedGoat 5 GTX Spiked Shoe

review.itemreviewed: Speedgoat 5 GTX Spike Trail Run Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: Overall, this is a good shoe. It does fit true to size in length, but the heel cup is too big for my heel. I've not had that problem with any shoe before so I feel like my foot is a standard foot. My heel comes up when I walk. I tried the runner's loop with it to keep my heel down. It made a little difference, but not much. I do have a pair of Speedgoat 5's and I don't have the heel cup problem with those. The spikes on the shoe are fantastic. They have been working well for me on slippery/muddy terrain. The shoe itself needs to be a bit lower or a bit higher at the ankle for me as it rubs my ankles wrong. I'd love to see this shoe as a high top for the ankle support. I've been wearing them in wet terrain and in the rain and my feet have remained dry.
review.name: Good, but could be better

review.itemreviewed: Speedgoat 5 GTX Spike Trail Run Shoe - Women's
review.reviewBody: I very much like the Hoka brand. Really comfortable for trail runs and hikes. The only problem I have is it's nearly impossible to wear gaiters because of the way the leasing structure is. Please hook up! Figure out how trail runners can wear gaiters with your shoes
review.name: Love them, but...

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Trainer 2 GTX Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I have worn this shoe on and off for almost two years and I have no complaints. It has a good grip, a very strong sole and still only showing light wear. The only thing wearing out is the shoe lace. The tongue of the shoe does a great job keeping grit out of the shoe and the sole performs well walking over small to medium rocky ground. The shoe breaths very well and it is waterproof for sure, all thanks to constructed with real Goretex. Plus they looks good. I have not put it though the wringer but I have worn it many times in all terrains to prove its versatility. A winner
review.name: A True Winner

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Trainer 2 GTX Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: These are nice shoes, but there's a caveat. If you ever need to replace the laces, be aware that Salewa doesn't stock orange replacement laces - just black ones. Big deal? Maybe. More importantly, the way the shoes are designed - without standard eyelets - you can't re-lace the shoes yourself without an engineering degree and a full set of power tools. And Salewa made it clear to me that they don't care - when I was lucky enough to actually get in touch with them. Bottom line? They should have proper replacement laces available, they should find a new shoe designer and they should pick up the phone and solve problems when loyal customers call.
review.name: Good shoes, but...

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Trainer 2 GTX Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I have an older pair of Mountain Trainers that aren?t waterproof and that can be finicky to get my heels locked in. I decided to give these a try, hoping that the fit would be the same or better. Nope! The heel counter is even shallower, not even coming close to going over the curve of my heel, and I don?t know WHAT the funky tongue is all about. There?s barely enough lace to tie. Overall the shoe feels slightly lower volume, just not what I need. Looks like I?ll be using my older pair for another year. 3 stars because they ARE good shoes, just apparently meant for people with 4 toes.
review.name: Not changed for the better for me
comment: I agree, they are lower volume. The rest of the shoe fit me fine... but because they are low volume with the tongue sewn all the way around they are too tight on my borderline narrow but high volume foot.

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Trainer 2 GTX Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody:
The items runs a bit small. I typically wear a size 12 in virtually all of my footwear and this one is closer to 1/2 size up.  Product looked decent but unsure how I like the tongue, feels like it doesn't pull up as far as others.

Returned due to lack of size 12.5 and customer svc was solid as usual.
review.name: Sizing

review.itemreviewed: Mountain Trainer 2 GTX Hiking Shoe - Men's
review.reviewBody: I planned to put  lock laces in the shoes like I did with my old pair, but the lock laces were to thick.  I had a frustrating experience putting the original laces back with tweezers.  The longevity of the shoe seems to be limited to the strength of the laces.
review.name: Don?t take out shoelace.
comment: I agree. The shoe definitely outlasts the laces. I wrote to Salewa directly. They sent me 2 new sets of laces at no cost to me. Best customer service ever.!

review.reviewBody: I look forward to using my HEST pad anytime I go camping, it's extremely comfortable, warm- perfect height off the ground- and QUIET....gone are the days of noisy air-inflated camping mattresses.
review.name: Better Than My Home Bed!

review.reviewBody: My back has taken a toll from skiing over the years and this mattress is the only camping pad that I can use for my bad back. I highly recommend this camping mattress for anyone who has any back pain or back issues. It is by far the best and most comfortable mattress you can get in the market. Believe me I have done my research to find a mattress that I can use camping with my back issues. Highly recommend.
review.name: Best camping mattress for back pain!

review.reviewBody: This mattress is more comfortable than my home bed AND it doubles as a water floatie in the summer. Some memory foam mattresses have me waking up sweaty when I sleep on them, but even in the heat of summer the sleep system stays cool. and in the fall when it starts to get cold it doesn't harden up like most memory foam. Worth the $$$ for actually getting a good night's sleep when camping.
review.name: totally worth the price!

review.reviewBody: I had purchased this mattress with the intention of having a "base camp" sleeping situation in the mountains that I wasn't planning on packing into my backpack for my days trips as I wanted to explore different areas from a single base point each day. When I came back exhausted from each trip I was so thankful to have such a supportive, comfortable, and warm mattress to sleep on each night. In previous years I had always used air or air/foam inflatable mattresses due to their light weight/packability. However, I never really got the overnight rest that I wanted and was always slightly cold/uncomfortable. The HEST sleep system has changed the game for me! Knowing that I had an awesome base camp to come back "home" to, I was able to push myself further on each day hike and that confidence made my trip that much better. Highly recommended!
review.name: AMAZING NIGHT'S SLEEP

review.reviewBody: I needed to up graded form my older Gregory 48 L pack I loved, I needed a little more room and this fit my requirements beautifully with more feature to make it easier to handle a load of stuff.  Looking forward to many good trips with my Paragon 68.  Also like the color choice both outside and inside.  I would buy this pack again or suggest it to a friend.
review.name: Happy Pack choice

review.reviewBody: Not quite an ultralight pack but also not a bulky pack. In my opinions this is the what 80% of backpackers want. Lighter than Mystery Ranch and more affordable than Osprey. The frame does a good job keeping the packs weight off your shoulders. I would recommend this for people who aren’t interested in sacrificing comfort on the trendy UL bags.
review.name: Light and comfortable

review.reviewBody: Only been out for a few weekend trips and one of them I was carrying gear for both myself and my son and it managed the weight very well!! I fully expect it to perform excellent on my next trip through the foothills trail. Middle of the road on pack weight but the quality it excellent.  Included a rain cover which I don’t really use (I prefer a liner) but many of my friends use. Great pack
review.name: Great pack, everything I have come to expect from Gregory

review.reviewBody: Perfect for hiking and carrying the items we needed!
Well made, lightweight, and l easy to access and adjust.  Perfect for a 2-4 nighter.

I’ve taken this pack on a few long hikes so far and I’ve really enjoyed the comfort and balance. The frame keeps the pack close and contoured to your back and the adjustments for fitting it to you work great. I had my pack weighed down with about 40 pounds on the longer hikes and it still provided good comfort on my back and hips. Definitely would recommend.
review.name: Solid and reliable

review.reviewBody: My son needed a backpack to grow into with Boy Scouts, previously using the Stout 65.  This pack with it's adjustability, especially in the hip belt, will allow him to grow from his 13-year old frame later into his teen years with a pack that can grow/shift with him.

This is a fantastic pack. I’ve owned the Baltoro 75 for about 7 years and this pack is an upgrade to that pack. It is a very simple pack without a lot of extra features, which I think is awesome. Took it on a short backpacking trip this last weekend and it was great size for the essentials as well as some luxury items. If you’re more of a minimalist the smaller 58L size would be perfect.

 It is very comfortable and the adjustability of fit on the back and hip belt are fantastic! The mesh back panel helps with breathability, but like most packs it will get warm. Overall it’s a very comfy pack even when packed to the brim. Tested it out on some prep hikes with around 25-35lbs and it was just as comfortable at 35lbs as it was at 25lbs. It also works great as a day pack for summit hikes while backpacking.  

I do wish that it had a few additional loops or tie points on the pack as well as a magnetic attachment for the bite valve of hydration packs, like the ones Gregory puts on some of their other packs. I also wish they had buckles on all the side compression straps, currently only the one that goes over the side pocket has a buckle. None of these things detract from the quality or comfort of the bag, they are just a few things I wish the pack had. Honestly, this pack is just a nice as the Baltoro series, but at a cheaper price tag and not as heavy.
review.name: Fantastic Pack At A Fantastic Price

review.reviewBody: Would highly recommend this backpack for backpacking trips or any travel in general. You can store a week or more worth of clothing and gear in this backpack. Aluminum frame supports your back and the hip straps take 80% of the weight off of your shoulders and transfer to your legs. I take this as a carry-on for flights and skip checking a bag for any trip over a week long.
review.name: Amazing for travel and backpacking

review.reviewBody: I have been able to use this bag on two trips now and it has been fantastically comfortable. I haven't gotten any bruises even when I used it for 3 days. My one complaint might be that the shoulder straps do slightly rub my shoulders a little wrong, but that could be more of a fit issue. The hit strap webbing is also very long. I might trim it down. I would definetly recommend trying a pack like this on in a store to make sure it fits well.
review.name: Fantastic pack

review.reviewBody: Just used it for the first time the other day on a ride in the low 50's and I was plenty warm with just a sleeveless base layer. It was sunny though. The wind proofing works great. Luckily I haven't had to use the waterproofing yet. As others have said the arms are quite tight. I feel like if I flexed too much I could blow them out but they are somewhat stretchy. review.reviewBody: Runs very small, the sleeves wouldn?t even go over my forearms

review.reviewBody: I'm 6' and 225 lbs with a bit of a gut, got an XXL, should probably have gotten 3XL. As mentioned by previous reviewer arms are very tight, and my arms are not big. I have to turn arms inside out to get off and should probably put it on that way. I don't think I could get the arms on whilst sweaty. Body is snug but reasonable. Once you wrestle this thing on and start riding the merits become obvious. The material is fantastic, wind proof but very breathable. It regulates my temperature really well while keeping the chill out. I would gladly buy this material on other garments with a more realistic fit. Haven't used in the rain yet.  I layer under it for fat tire riding and it works great. If Castelli made a "recreational" cut version its easily 5 stars. We're not all built like racers, some of us are just trying to stay in shape.
review.name: Great jacket but snug

review.reviewBody: This seems like a very well made and comfortable jacket, but the arms are so skinny I couldn't even get it on. And my arms aren't by any means screaming that I go to the gym; they are very average. You kinda need to be a spider (or have a slender, typically cyclist body frame) for this to work. If you are an average built individual like I am, this probably won't work.

review.itemreviewed: Echo Lace SJ BOA Snowboard Boot - 2024 - Men's
Echo Lace SJ BOA Snowboard Boot - 2024 - Men's
review.reviewBody:
I have been snowboarding for 23 years and this is possibly the worst designed boot i have ever ridden.
Buyer beware this boot is sold as ‘stiff’ but is in-fact extremely soft. It feels like these boots have been ridden for multiple seasons and are wildly unresponsive. It takes a single day to blow them out and turn them into expensive slippers. 
These are basically a copy of the Vans infuse but done very badly and lazily. The liner tightening technology is absolutely atrocious as it does not attach to the boot shell so you will ALWAYS have heel lift. Actually the tighter you make your liner (thus making it smaller) the worse you make the fit…
The eyelits on the foot are extremely slick so its very difficult to sinch your foot properly which is extremely important. 
Conversly the top eyelits are very grabby and do not allow the boot to naturally balance out. This creates pressure points and an overall uncomfortable ride. 
These boots were clearly designed by somone who had never been snowboarding before. Making a boot that is both too soft to snowboard in and wildly uncomfortable is actually very impressive…
review.name: Extremely soft; Constant heel lift

review.itemreviewed: Echo Lace SJ BOA Snowboard Boot - 2024 - Men's
review.reviewBody:
Have a couple days on them so far & break in is coming along. 
Fit is top notch. Slim through the ankle, good hold with the harness. Toe box has a little height to it (which I am a fan of). 
I will say this boot at least starts out stiff. Will see where it ends up after a few days, but would say it's not as stiff as a Malamute, but probably a second in line for stiffness. 
Added powerstrap at the top is a bonus!
review.name: All the features & great fit

review.reviewBody: These are just fantastic! Unbeatable for the price & quality. Read a lot of reviews prior to buying and I see what many folks said in regards to the lack of drop tail capability HOWEVER they drop just fine for me. Because the fabric has good stretch to it, I'm able to pull them down and slide the backside across the bum and easily have them pulled down and over enough for a quick squat. As I run very cold on the mtn, this was a huge factor in if I was going to keep them or try to consign locally (as they're a final sale item here), and with that said I'm frothing to wear them this winter and couldn't be more stoked on the fit, color, and easy of access. That said, if you have a good seamstress you could easily have the side zipper altered to extend down a couple inches (shown in picture) that would really make the side squat guaranteed for all. Reference, in 5'2" 100lbs, bought size xs reg length.  I'm also digging the lack of buckle or snaps on the shoulder straps as I see now they're really unnecessary and will not have to worry about my hair getting stuck in strap buckles. 10/10 (caveat, not sure how warm they will end up being but I usually only wear 15k max gear with warm baselayers)

review.reviewBody:
I absolutely loved my original fireball bibs, and decided it was time for a new pair... I couldn't be more disappointed. All of my favorite features don't exist in these bibs. Where did the drop seat go? I loved having the ability to NOT have to get entirely undressed to go pee, not worrying about if my shoulder straps are being dragged across the bathroom floor. Where did the beautifully stretchy waistband go? It was so comfy, easy to put my arm in to adjust clothing layers, bend, sit... I could squat to help my kids get their boots buckled, twist and bend with ease, to strap in and out without being sliced through my middle. Where did the full leg zippers go? Oh to be able to get a wicked vent going as needed or just pop some space into the knee for a full squat to wrestle a child into their boots, pants, coat, mittens, helmet... I didn't know how lucky I was.

But alas, I am a woman, so I should have expected that I couldn't return to a product I loved and have it be the same as I had left it, I should have known better.
review.name: Firefall/2 lost all of the best features of the original

review.reviewBody: I have these bibs from a couple years ago and wanted to buy another pair in a new size because I love my old ones so much. Why, I ask, WHY did you change the design?? It's AWFUL. Taking away the drop-seat was a fatal mistake in my book. The drop-seat is a "make or break" feature that dictates whether I'll buy or not. It's already a struggle for women to use the bathroom in full ski gear and in these newly designed bibs, it's virtually impossible.
review.name: Took away the drop-seat; mistake

review.reviewBody:
I generally love Mountain Hardwear, but felt like I needed to review these! Not a fan. Trying them on, I didn’t feel like they were super tight. Unfortunately, with the location of the zipper on the side and the constant bending over to unlatch/relatch snowboard straps, the zipper has been busting open every time I move now. I also usually wear a size 6 (5’ 2” and 160 lbs, hips are 38, waist is 34) and I don’t usually have to size up to a large (generally wear size small or medium leggings, etc.) but if you have any sort of weight on our hips or stomach I would because of this issue. They are not as forgiving as I’d hope for lots of bending over movements :(

Similarly, because the zipper is so small, they can’t be easily repaired - not only does the actual zipper part come loose, but the pulling on the teeth has made them super wonky in one spot. No matter how much I re-line the zipper, it still catches in this one spot.
review.name: Not recommended for snowboarding :(

review.reviewBody: When out on the mountain, it is often the little details that can make or break the day. For instance, having to completely disrobe to go to the restroom in full gear is undesirable. I truly cannot believe you made the decision to remove the drop seat from a pair of excellent bibs. It essentially renders them useless. On top of the removal of the drop seat, you, as a product development team, decided to make the shoulder straps non detachable which makes it even more challenging to take the pants off. I and all other mountain hardware customers who have purchased these bibs that are a crime against all people ask that you do not produce bibs in the future without these functional details. In a time of making strides as a society, these are a step backward. Additionally the mid section is small which the rest of the bib is huge. I hope you keep customers and their experience at the forefront for next season.
review.name: Updated design for the worst

review.name: Great walking shoe

review.reviewBody: The strap across the top of the shoe tongue is too tight, even with the laces completely loosened. I returned the shoes.
review.name: Too Tight across the top of the air

review.reviewBody: Initially, this shoe was perfect for the multiple uses I had intended to wear it: Walking around campus, a little light trail walking, running errands, etc. The GTX material means it's not very breathable during the summer months, but it's moderate plushiness makes up for it in terms of comfort. To me, it was a versatile, all-around, great sneaker. However, one of the shoes randomly developed a very loud "squeak" about 4 months after purchase. I believe an air pocket developed in the sole, but I cannot be certain and despite my research, I cannot make it stop. Unfortunately, the squeakiness has made the shoe nearly unwearable as I have to walk in an uncomfortable way to make it stop. As I stated, I initially loved these shoes. They were everything I had wanted and expected. But the squeak drives me, and the people around me, so insane I honestly don't know if I'd ever invest in Hokas again.
review.name: Initially great, but its squeakiness drives me insane

review.reviewBody: Loved these at first, but the strap on my shoe broke in two months. Squeeky noise won't go away. Probably the worst hokas I've owned! Save your money for some different hokas.
review.name: Broke in about 2 months

review.reviewBody: I purchased these shoes and was excited. I put them on and went on the 12.5-mile walk I do daily. When I went to take my shoes off, the quick draw shoelace system that came with the shoe comletely broke. I had to swap them out for the laces completely. I knew eventually I would probably need to replace the quick-release laces that came with the shoes, I just thought for the price, they would last longer than 1 walk or 3 hours. Love the color and styling. Find them a bit snug width-wise.
review.name: The Quick Tie Broke first work out

review.reviewBody: I thought this shoe was very suitable for traveling. I usually wear size 8.5. After receiving the shoe, I felt it was a little small, so I changed to size 9. It is very comfortable to wear, but it is a little narrow in the front, which is not a problem.
review.name: Good design shoes

review.reviewBody: Everyone said that HOKA's were super comfortable, unfortunately that's not my experience. I bought premium shoes hoping they would feel great, however, they give me pain in my arches, too narrow, ( yet I do not have wide feet ) and feel odd under the toes. I was hoping to use them for walking / all around...but I'll need to replace them.
review.name: Not what I expected

review.reviewBody: I ordered the Transport GTX with hope that I could wear it on an upcoming vacation where rain is anticipated. I like the look and feel, but the right foot towbox cover tents down when walking and makes a very annoying snapping noise. I returned the first pair and received a replacement and low and behold, it has the same problem. I have worn HOKA shoes for years and know the size and fit well. I returned the Transport GTX again and will order another shoe model Challenger without Goretex even though it comes in GTX.
review.name: Needs some more design work on the tow box!

review.reviewBody: I've had a pair of transport GTX for over a year. My go to shoe for walking, sometimes hiking. So, I know it's a good product. My newly purchased pair left me puzzled. The left shoe sounded like a flip flop with. every. step! My return was easy, pretty sure the exchanged pair will be fine.
review.name: Great product, bad example

review.reviewBody: I recently purchased a pair of Hoka Transports. I liked them so much that I bought another pair and upgraded to GTX. What a dissapointment. The GTX hurt my feet. I alternate wearing my Transport and my GTX. The Transorts are comfortable. The GTX hurt. I will be testing Hoka's return policy. I can't wear these shoes.
review.name: Hoka GTX Transport is narower than the Hoka Transport

review.reviewBody: They feel and fit like cheaper nylon socks that you would wear with a suit and tie. Just not feeling the tech I would expect.
review.name: Average at best

review.reviewBody: Two rides in and they are already showing signs of extreme use... Total of 100 miles road riding between the two rides. Save your money and get some Swiftwick socks.
review.name: Wear Out Quickly

review.reviewBody: Wish I had read some reviews before purchase. These look great and feel fine but wear out after a few rides. Mainly using these on road rides so I'm sure they would wear out quicker on dirt. Also not as snug as I would like. Better socks out there for the money.
review.name: Quick to wear out!

review.reviewBody: They are falling apart after a couple of rides. Nice while new though
review.name: Nice while they last..

review.reviewBody:
Nothing wrong here; fit is good, sock is somewhat supportive, and wicks adequately.  I wrote the review to encourage anyone reading this to look at other options - in this price range and similar height/weight, I've found socks that I think are MUCH nicer: better feel, more support, better wicking performance (fizik and Shimano would be two examples).  

If you wish to sport the Giro logo or just like grey stripes, this is fine and is reasonably priced.
review.name: Average.  Others are better.

review.reviewBody: Love these socks. Height is taller than most crew socks, which I really like. Great fit, comfortable and look good. I wear these cycling, running and to the gym.
review.name: Perfect Height
